Wash and dry all produce. Halve, peel, and thinly slice @shallot{1}. Zest and
halve @lime{1}. Thinly slice @jalapeño{1} into rounds, removing ribs and seeds
for less heat.

In a #small bowl{}, combine shallot, juice from whole lime, @sugar{1/4%tsp},
a pinch of @salt{}, and as much jalapeño as you like. Set aside to pickle,
stirring occasionally, until ready to serve.

In a second small bowl, combine @sour cream{4%tbsp}, @chili powder{1/4%tsp},
@salt{}, @pepper{}, and lime zest to taste. Add @water{} 1 tsp at a time until
mixture reaches a drizzling consistency.

Drain @corn{13.4%oz}, then pat very dry with #paper towels{}. Heat a #large dry pan{}
(preferably nonstick; if not, add a drizzle of @vegetable oil{1%tsp}) over
medium-high heat. Add corn and cook, without stirring, until browned on bottom,
~{3-4%minutes}. Continue to cook, stirring, until charred all over, ~{3-4%minutes}
more. Turn off heat; transfer to a #medium bowl{}.

> The drier your corn, the less likely it is to pop in the pan.

Heat @butter{1%tbsp} and a drizzle of oil in same pan over medium-high heat.
Add @ground pork{10%oz} and a pinch of salt and pepper. Cook, breaking up meat
into pieces, until browned, ~{4-6%minutes}. Stir in @Southwest spice blend{1%tbsp}
and @chili powder{1/4%tsp}. Cook until fragrant, ~{1%minute}. Stir in
@chicken stock concentrate{1} and @water{1/4%cup}. Cook until liquid has mostly
reduced and pork is cooked through, ~{2-3%minutes}. Turn off heat.

Reserving veggies, pour pickling liquid to taste into bowl with corn. Stir in
a drizzle of @olive oil{1%tsp}, remaining chili powder, and a big pinch of salt
and pepper. Wrap @flour tortillas{6} in damp paper towels and microwave until
warm and pliable, ~{30%seconds}. Divide tortillas between plates and fill with
pork and corn. Top with crema and as many pickled veggies as you like. Serve.